{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19591"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.09,0.91,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99823"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82210"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29488"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99823"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 49-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with progressive abdominal swelling and weight gain over three months. He has no abdominal pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He drinks two bottles of wine per day. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears chronically unwell. His vital signs are within normal limits. His abdomen is distended with shifting dullness and a fluid thrill. There are dilated subcutaneous veins radiating from the umbilicus. He has bilateral gynaecomastia, palmar erythema, and spider naevi on his chest (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple obesity","Budd-Chiari syndrome","Cirrhosis","Carcinoma of the pancreas","Pseudomyxoma peritonei"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of portal hypertension secondary to liver cirrhosis. The combination of ascites, caput medusae (dilated periumbilical veins), gynaecomastia, palmar erythema, and spider naevi strongly suggests chronic liver disease. His significant alcohol intake is likely the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E leads to portal hypertension, which causes ascites through a combination of increased hydrostatic pressure and altered sodium handling. The development of collateral circulation around the umbilicus (caput medusae) occurs as blood seeks alternative routes around the obstructed portal system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple obesity\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the presence of dilated abdominal wall vessels, gynaecomastia, or other signs of chronic liver disease. The distribution of fat in obesity is typically different from ascites and would not demonstrate shifting dullness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudd-Chiari syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, while causing ascites due to hepatic vein obstruction, is a rare condition that typically presents more acutely with abdominal pain and hepatomegaly. It would be unlikely to present with such established signs of chronic liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ascites but usually presents with significant weight loss rather than weight gain. It would not explain the other signs of chronic liver disease present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomyxoma peritonei\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition characterised by mucinous ascites from a ruptured appendiceal or ovarian tumour. It would not cause the systemic signs of chronic liver disease seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ascites with dilated subcutaneous veins and gynaecomastia are characteristic features of portal hypertension due to cirrhosis.","Physical examination findings of cirrhosis include caput medusae, spider naevi, palmar erythema, and gynaecomastia.","The most common causes of cirrhosis are alcohol-related liver disease, viral hepatitis, and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease."],"references":["Gin\u00e8s P, Krag A, Abraldes JG, Sol\u00e0 E, Fabrellas N, Kamath PS. Liver cirrhosis. Lancet. 2021;398(10308):1359-1376. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(21)01374-X","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82210"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19591"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21862"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21862"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RtOHS0k43JcLW6JTfoBrX7MYxXzxgL.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RtOHS0k43JcLW6JTfoBrX7MYxXzxgL.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":424,"height":522}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevision